/**
  @page guides-index General concepts
  @brief General concepts and design of Rodin features.

  @tableofcontents

  @section guides-getting-started-index Getting started with Rodin

  New to Rodin? Start here for a comprehensive introduction:

  Welcome to Rodin! This guide will help you get started with the Rodin
  finite element framework. Whether you're new to finite element methods or
  an experienced practitioner, these guides will walk you through the
  essentials of using Rodin effectively.

  @subsection guides-getting-started-overview What you'll learn

  This Getting Started guide is organized into several sections that will take
  you from installation to solving your first finite element problem:

  - @subpage guides-getting-started-installation - How to install Rodin and set up
    your development environment

  - @subpage guides-getting-started-first-steps - Basic concepts and your first Rodin
    program

  - @subpage guides-getting-started-first-problem - Solving a complete problem: the
    Poisson equation

  - @subpage guides-getting-started-core-concepts - Understanding meshes, finite
    element spaces, and variational formulations


  @subsection guides-getting-started-prerequisites Prerequisites

  Before starting, you should have:
  - Basic knowledge of C++
  - Familiarity with finite element methods (recommended but not required)
  - A Linux or macOS system with a C++20 compatible compiler

  @subsection guides-getting-started-next-steps After completing this guide

  Once you've completed the Getting Started guide, you can:
  - Explore more @ref examples-index "examples" to see Rodin in action
  - Read the @ref guides-index "general concepts" for deeper understanding
  - Check out the API reference for detailed information on specific classes
    and functions

  @subsection guides-getting-started-help Getting help

  If you encounter any issues:
  - Check the [GitHub repository](https://github.com/cbritopacheco/rodin)
  - Look at the @ref examples-index "examples" for similar use cases
  - Review the @ref guides-index "guides" for conceptual explanations

  @section guides-geometry-index Geometry

  The Geometry module provides comprehensive support for mesh generation, manipulation,
  and geometric computations in finite element analysis.

  For detailed information on specific geometry topics, see:

  - @subpage guides-meshes - Working with meshes

  - @subpage guides-polytopes - Geometric elements and their properties

  - @subpage guides-connectivity - Detailed connectivity information

  @section guides-fem-index The finite element method

  These guides cover the mathematical foundations of the finite element method
  and how they are implemented in Rodin:

  - @subpage fem-ciarlet - The formal definition of a finite element

  - @subpage fem-spaces - Overview of available finite element spaces (P0, P1,
    vector-valued, complex-valued)

  @section guides-variational-index Weak formulations and variational problems

  Understand how to translate PDEs into variational problems that can be
  solved using the finite element method:

  - @subpage guides-variational - Defining bilinear forms, linear forms,
    boundary conditions, and solving variational problems

  - @subpage guides-weak-formulations - From strong form to weak form

  - @subpage guides-boundary-conditions - Applying Dirichlet, Neumann, and
    mixed boundary conditions

  - @subpage guides-solvers - Direct and iterative solvers for the assembled
    linear systems

  @section guides-io-index I/O in Rodin

  Rodin provides flexible I/O capabilities for reading and writing meshes,
  grid functions, and simulation data in various formats:

  - @subpage guides-io - Comprehensive guide to input and output, including
    XDMF, MFEM, and MEDIT formats

  */

